"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038951","Home Office","false","2019-01-15","<p>HM Passport Office (HMPO) has an ambitious transformation plan to increase digital applications, helping to reduce operational expenditure by removing paper and customer errors from the process.</p><p>In June 2016, HMPO launched its first fully digital online application service for adults renewing their passport. This launch was supported by no cost communications activity, including PR and stakeholder engagement. Last financial year (2017/18) a small scale paid search campaign, costing £9,665, was trialled to encourage customers to use the online application channel. In this financial year (2018/19) a marketing campaign, costing £536,639.04, was delivered via radio and digital advertising.</p><p>A re-launch of the marketing campaign in 2019/20 has been planned, forecast at £1m. This activity is dependent on the outcome of the EU Exit withdrawal agreement.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038951/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-15T17:04:22.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038951/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038951/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-01-10","Passports: Applications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what funds his Department has spent on advertisements promoting online passport applications in each of the last three years; and what funds he plans to spend on promoting online passport applications in the next financial year.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","207212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038952","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-15","<p>We have had no correspondence with NHS England or NHS Improvement regarding the Nuffield Trust’s analysis, dated 26 October 2018. We do not agree there is a shortfall in 2019-20, and the aforementioned analysis concludes that once recurrent efficiencies are factored in, there is financial headroom within the National Health Service long term settlement.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038952/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-15T12:30:56.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038952/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038952/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-10","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if his Department will publish correspondence with (a) NHS England and (b) NHS Improvement on any (i) assessment and (b) analysis that indicates a funding shortfall of more than £1 billion in 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","207213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038953","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-01-18","<p>​We continue to monitor issues and cases involving Nubians and other minorities within Egypt. Egypt is a human rights priority country for the UK and the UK wants to see more political progress and better protection of human rights for all Egyptians, as set out in Egypt's constitution. The UK regularly raise concerns about human rights with the Egyptian Government both in public and in private. I raised our human rights concerns with the Egyptian Foreign Minister during my visit to Cairo on 14 October 2018.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038953/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-18T11:44:41.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038953/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038953/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-10","Egypt: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has made a recent assessment of the effect on the human rights of (a) the Nubian people and (b) other political dissenters of the Egyptian Government's alleged persecution of those people; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","207214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038954","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-01-15","<p>Reports of the number of detainees, deaths and injuries vary. On 12 January the Government of Sudan reported that 24 deaths had occurred. Activist groups and Non-Governmental Organisations assess the number to be considerably higher. We are unable to verify these figures independently, but we continue to express our deep concern at the current situation, both bilaterally and as part of the Troika (with the USA and Norway). We are urging the Government of Sudan to respect the Sudanese people's right to freedom of expression and peaceful assembly, and to ensure those responsible for the deaths of protestors are held to account. We expect political activists, human rights defenders, journalists and others who are being detained without charge or trial to be released immediately, and for all detainees to be treated in accordance with international standards. We continue to monitor the situation closely.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038954/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-15T16:30:01.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038954/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038954/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-10","Sudan: Demonstrations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many protesters have been reported to have been (a) detained, (b) tortured and (c) killed by Sudanese authorities since demonstrations began on 19 December 2018; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","207146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038955","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-01-15","<p>On 9 January the British Ambassador registered the UK's concern directly with Sudan's Acting Foreign Minister regarding the level of violence used to disperse peaceful protests in Sudan. He reiterated the messages in the public statement made by the Troika (Norway/ UK/ US) and Canada on 8 January urging the government to respect the Sudanese people's right to freedom of expression and peaceful assembly, and to ensure those responsible for the deaths of protestors are held to account.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038955/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-15T16:33:53.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038955/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038955/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-10","Sudan: Demonstrations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Sudanese counterpart on the Sudanese authorities' response to the protests in that country.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","207147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038956","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-01-15","<p>​We continue to monitor closely the Government of Sudan's response to the recent protests, and to express our concern at the current situation, both bilaterally and as part of the Troika with the US and Norway. As we made clear with Troika partners and Canada in our statement of 8 January, the Government of Sudan's response to these protests will have an impact on the approach to engagement of our governments and others in the coming months and years.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038956/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-15T16:35:17.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038956/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038956/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-10","Sudan: Demonstrations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what effect the (a) response of the Government of Sudan to the recent protests in that country and (b) Troika government's statement published on 8 January 2019 will have on the UK-Sudan Strategic Dialogue due to take place in 2019.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","207148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038957","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-01-15","<p>There are no current joint security programmes between the UK and Government of Sudan. The extent of UK funded defence engagement with the Government of Sudan is limited to the provision of a small scale education programme to the regular Sundanese armed forces that focuses on International Humanitarian Law, the Law of Armed Conflict and on Governance and Security Sector Reform. This is achieved through the teaching of English language and graduate-level lectures, using professionally qualified teachers, academics and lawyers.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038957/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-15T16:36:41.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038957/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038957/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-10","Sudan: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what joint programmes on security are ongoing between the UK Government and the Government of Sudan.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","207149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038958","House of Commons Commission","false","2019-01-17","<p>The Pass Office recently introduced a Netcall telephone management system in order to monitor calls. In general, this shows that the Pass Office is receiving an increased volume of calls. This reflects a 17% increase in the number of pass applications, from 10,849 in 2017 to 12,940 in 2018. In particular, the Pass Office experienced a large increase in calls following the Christmas break. This coincided with a period when the Pass Office was suffering from staff shortages. While this is now being addressed, it has meant that the office currently has fewer people dedicated to responding to calls, as the back-office team also perform duties such as processing security clearance applications.</p><p>The Pass Office is keen to ensure good customer service. As calls to the Pass Office are often to check on the status of applications, callers are being advised to email the Pass Office with the relevant information. This is so that Pass Office staff can then respond more effectively and swiftly to these enquiries. The Pass Office encourages e-mail enquiries as the best way customers can get a quick update on the status of an application.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038958/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-17T20:05:34.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038958/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038958/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2019-01-10","Parliamentary Estate: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington, representing the House of Commons Commission, what recent assessment the Commission has made of the efficiency of call-handling procedures in the House of Commons Pass Office.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","207164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038959","Cabinet Office","false","2019-01-17","<p>The Civil Contingencies Secretariat sits within the wider National Security Secretariat. The budget<br>for the Civil Contingencies Secretariat (CCS) for 2016-2017, 2017-2018 and 2018-2019 is set out<br>in the table below;</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Total Budget</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-2017</p></td><td><p>£11.9 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-2018</p></td><td><p>£15,4 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018-2019</p></td><td><p>£16.9 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The current delegated headcount for CCS is 94. This is the maximum number of staff paid out of the CCS budget, it does not include staff working in or with the Secretariat paid for by other departments or programmes.</p><p><strong></strong><br><br></p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038959/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-17T10:12:41.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038959/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038959/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-01-10","Civil Contingencies Secretariat: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people currently work in the civil contingencies secretariat.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","207215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038960","Cabinet Office","false","2019-01-17","<p>The Civil Contingencies Secretariat sits within the wider National Security Secretariat. The budget for the Civil Contingencies Secretariat (CCS) for 2016-2017, 2017-2018 and 2018-2019 is set out in the table below;</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Total Budget</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-2017</p></td><td><p>£11.9 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-2018</p></td><td><p>£15,4 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018-2019</p></td><td><p>£16.9 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The current delegated headcount for CCS is 94. This is the maximum number of staff paid out of the CCS budget, it does not include staff working in or with the Secretariat paid for by other departments or programmes.</p><p> </p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038960/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-17T10:14:39.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038960/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038960/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-01-10","Civil Contingencies Secretariat: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the civil contingencies secretariat budget was for (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18 and (c) 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","207216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038961","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-17","<p>The volume of NHS 111 calls which were abandoned after at least 30 seconds connection time to the NHS 111 service from January to December 2018 is shown in the following table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Month</p></td><td><p>Volume of calls abandoned after at least 30 seconds</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2018</p></td><td><p>75,488</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>February 2018</p></td><td><p>88,544</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March 2018</p></td><td><p>113,244</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2018</p></td><td><p>45,718</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May 2018</p></td><td><p>43,485</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>June 2018</p></td><td><p>46,702</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July 2018</p></td><td><p>62,784</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>August 2018</p></td><td><p>41,646</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September 2018</p></td><td><p>37,697</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October 2018</p></td><td><p>44,697</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>November 2018</p></td><td><p>50,703</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December 2018</p></td><td><p>57,375</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: NHS England, NHS 111 minimum data set</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/nhs-111-minimum-data-set/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/nhs-111-minimum-data-set/</a></p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038961/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-17T16:30:24.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038961/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038961/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-10","NHS 111","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many calls to 111 were abandoned in each month in 2018.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","207217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038962","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-17","<p>The question is interpreted as requesting detail regarding the level of income generated from the treatment of private patients by each National Health Service trust. This is presented in the attached tables for the financial years 2010-11 to 2017-18.</p><p> </p><p>Prior to 2010-11 the Department’s Annual Report and Accounts did not report ‘income from private patients’ as a specific line item and thus comparable information for prior years is unable to be provided.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038962/answer","PQ207218 - Data tables.docx","PQ207218 - Data tables.docx","PQ207218 attached document","PQ207218 attached document",,"2019-01-17T11:58:47.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038962/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038962/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-10","Private Patients","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate he has made of income from private patients at each NHS Trust for each of the last ten years for which records are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","207218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038963","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-17","<p>The Department does not hold the information in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>However, the following table shows the number of nurses and health visitors in National Health Service trusts and clinical commissioning groups in England in the last 10 years as at September each year, full time equivalent:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>September-2008</p></td><td><p>281,021</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September-2009</p></td><td><p>278,470</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September-2010</p></td><td><p>279,883</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September-2011</p></td><td><p>277,047</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September-2012</p></td><td><p>271,407</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September-2013</p></td><td><p>274,627</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September-2014</p></td><td><p>278,981</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September-2015</p></td><td><p>281,474</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September-2016</p></td><td><p>284,288</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September-2017</p></td><td><p>283,853</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September-2018</p></td><td><p>285,674</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: NHS Hospital and Community Health Service workforce statistics, NHS Digital</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038963/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-17T16:12:05.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038963/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038963/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-10","Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate he has made of the number of nurses employed in the NHS per head of population for each of the last ten years for which records are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","207219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038964","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-17","<p>The Department does not hold the data requested.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will support the National Health Service to ensure that the right staff, with the right skills and experience, are available to deliver the high-quality care the public expects. This includes building on the work already underway to recruit, train and retain more staff to address shortages. This will involve more training places with increased flexibility, including for those high priority areas such as mental health and primary care, as well as new or expanded roles with greater opportunities for career progression for existing staff.</p><p> </p><p>To ensure a detailed plan that everyone in the NHS can get behind, the Secretary of State has commissioned Baroness Harding to lead a rapid and inclusive programme of work to set out a detailed workforce implementation plan to be published in the spring.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038964/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-17T16:10:46.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038964/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038964/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-10","NHS: Vacancies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate he has made of the number of vacancies in the NHS by 2030 based upon workforce assumptions in the NHS Long Term Plan.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","207220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038965","Treasury","false","2019-01-15","<p>We are committed to our Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies around the globe. Enabling them to design and mint their own versions of the iconic new £1 coin is a demonstration of that commitment.</p><p>Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies will now be able to apply to the Royal Mint for permission to produce their own 12-sided pound coins. It is for the coin issuing authority in each of the Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies to seek permission, if they wish to do so.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038965/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-15T14:14:53.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038965/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038965/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-10","Coinage: British Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to his Department's announcement entitled New pound coin goes global with rollout to British overseas nations, published on 6 January 2019, if he will list which authority in each of the Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies that will be responsible for commissioning new £1 coins.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","207221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038966","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-01-17","<p>The number of reindeer and the number of consignments imported into the UK in 2018 is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Country from</p></td><td><p>Consignments</p></td><td><p>Animals</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Finland</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>31</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Germany</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Netherlands</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018 Total</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>47</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA) are not able to provide any data regarding the number of imports from third countries, as these are covered by a commodity code in TRACES which will not allow us to break the species down as far as reindeer for third country imports.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038966/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-17T14:28:41.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038966/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038966/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-01-10","Reindeer: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many reindeer in how many consignments and from which countries were imported into the UK in 2018; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","207150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038967","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-01-17","<p>The number of reindeer and the number of consignments exported from the UK in 2018 is as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Country of Destination</p></td><td><p>Number of Consignments</p></td><td><p>Number of Reindeers</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>France</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA) can access information using TRACES (Trade Control and Expert System) for species of animals that require a health certificate for movement to the EU.</p><p> </p><p>APHA records Export Health Certificates (EHC) issued for animals to third countries that do not use the TRACES system. There are no exports of reindeer to third countries recorded in 2018.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038967/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-17T12:59:34.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038967/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038967/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-01-10","Reindeer: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many reindeer in how many consignments and to which countries were exported from the UK in 2018; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","207152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038968","Department for International Development","false","2019-01-15","<p>There has not been an opportunity for the Secretary of State to meet G7 or G20 counterparts collectively since the launch of the Global Nutrition Report on 29 November 2018. The Government will continue to press at G7 and G20 meetings for greater priority to be given to malnutrition in all its forms, as the Report recommends. Following the G20 Summit on 30 November and 1 December, the Leaders statement reaffirmed the G20’s commitment in this regard. The Government also continues to raise nutrition with G7 and G20 partners bilaterally. For example, the UK Japan Joint Statement issued on the occasion of Prime Minister Abe’s visit on 10 January 2019 committed the UK and Japan to work together toward the success of the Global Nutrition Summit in Tokyo in 2020.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038968/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-15T15:30:53.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038968/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038968/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-01-10","Developing Countries: Malnutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent discussions she has had with her counterparts in (a) the G20 and (b) the G7 on addressing malnutrition since the publication of the 2018 Global Nutrition Report.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","207222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038969","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-01-18","<p>The Secretary of State attended the Ministerial Reoffending Board on 26<sup>th</sup> November, along with the Secretary of State for Justice. A range of issues were discussed, including improving access to employment for ex-offenders.</p><p> </p><p>This Government recognises that supporting ex-offenders into work is a crucial part of effective rehabilitation. DWP officials work closely with their counterparts in MoJ to improve the outcomes for ex–offenders. The DWP has dedicated Prison Work Coaches based in resettlement prisons across Great Britain, who work with prisoners, prison services, local partners and employers to help secure training, work experience and employment opportunities. Ex-offenders are also entitled to tailored support from Jobcentre Work Coaches and early, priority access to the Work and Health Programme.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038969/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-18T12:20:20.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038969/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038969/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-01-10","Employment: Offenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Justice on improving access to employment for ex-offenders.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","207275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038970","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-01-17","<p>Currently, there are 130 work coaches based in prisons in England, Scotland and Wales. Of these, 49 work in prisons on a full time basis and the others work on a part time basis. In total this is the equivalent of 107 full time members of staff.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038970/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-17T17:41:52.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038970/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038970/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-01-10","Prisons: Vocational Guidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many work coaches currently work in UK prisons on a full-time basis.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","207276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038971","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-01-16","<p>This Government recognises that supporting ex-offenders into work is a crucial part of effective rehabilitation. That is why Ministry of Justice launched the Education and Employment strategy to create a system where each prisoner is set on a path to employment as soon as they enter prison.</p><p> </p><p>It is also why the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) has dedicated Prison Work Coaches based in resettlement prisons across Great Britain, who work with prisoners, prison services, local partners and employers to help secure training, work experience and employment opportunities for prisoners at the start of their sentence, during their sentence and after release.</p><p> </p><p>Ex-offenders are also entitled to tailored support from Jobcentre Work Coaches and early, priority access to the Work and Health Programme, to ensure they receive more intensive employment support.</p><p> </p><p>DWP does not currently collate data to identify an ex-offender in a way that allows robust reporting. We are therefore committed to gathering better data to support claimants with complex needs and has prioritised this as part of the wider work programme for Universal Credit.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038971/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-16T16:14:20.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038971/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038971/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-01-10","Employment: Offenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment she has made of the effectiveness of policies to help former prisoners find employment.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","207277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038972","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-01-17","<p>We know that of those released in the 2011/12 tax year, a higher proportion of female offenders were claiming out-of-work benefits both before and after their caution/conviction or prison sentence, than male offenders.</p><p> </p><p>The proportion of women claiming out-of-work benefits in the month before receiving a conviction/caution or prison sentence was 53%, which increases by two percentage points to 55% one month after a conviction/caution or release from prison.</p><p> </p><p>We are aware of a number of barriers that prevent women from entering employment on release from prison and are working to address these issues.</p><p> </p><p>Last May, we published the Education and Employment strategy which aims to set each prisoner on a path to employment, with prison education and work geared towards employment on release from the outset.</p><p> </p><p>Our strategy includes a range of initiatives to support this ambition. For example, we are empowering governors to commission education provision that leads to work, we are encouraging employers to take on ex-prisoners via the New Futures Network (NFN) and we have consulted governors and employers on proposals to increase the opportunities available to prisoners to gain experience in real workplaces through ROTL.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038972/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-17T17:12:55.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038972/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038972/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-01-10","Offenders: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent assessment he has made of trends in the number of female offenders who have been unable to enter employment upon leaving prison.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","207278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038973","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-01-17","<p>We do not hold the data as requested, but we do know that offenders who find employment on release from prison are less likely to reoffend than those who do not.</p><p> </p><p>Offenders who found P45 employment in the twelve months after release from prison had one year re-offending rates that were 6-9 percentage points lower than similar offenders who did not find employment.</p><p> </p><p>In order to improve employment opportunities for ex-offenders, we published the Education and Employment strategy last year to set each prisoner on a path to employment from the outset, thus increasing access to employment for ex-offenders.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038973/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-17T17:15:39.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038973/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038973/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-01-10","Offenders: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many female offenders who have received more than one custodial sentence since 2010 were unemployed when they re-offended.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","207279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038974","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-01-16","<p>Each Member State implements the permanent residence requirements of the Free Movement Directive (2004/38/EC) differently and information is not held centrally on the fees charged for equivalent documents. For example, the Netherlands currently charge €51 for permanent residency, and this charge will remain the same for obtaining a status under the Withdrawal Agreement.</p><p>Country-specific information, where available, is detailed in the ‘Living in Guides’ which you can find at:</p><p><a href="https://bit.ly/2PJAHjx" target="_blank">https://bit.ly/2PJAHjx</a></p><p>The Free Movement Directive sets out the registration requirements and the rules of charging for permanent residence that Member States must follow in their processes.</p><p>Under this Directive, a Member State can require a person living there for more than three months to register within a time frame, which should be no less than three months from the date of their arrival. The Directive also states that a citizen’s possession of such registration documents cannot be a precondition for exercising their Treaty rights. It provides that all documents, including registration certificates and permanent residence documents, shall be issued free of charge or for a charge that is no more than that which nationals of the Member State pay for a similar documents.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038974/answer",,,,,"207281","2019-01-16T16:24:15.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038974/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038974/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-01-10","Emigration: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, in which European Union member states do British citizens have to register their details with the Government upon moving to that country.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","207280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038975","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-01-16","<p>Each Member State implements the permanent residence requirements of the Free Movement Directive (2004/38/EC) differently and information is not held centrally on the fees charged for equivalent documents. For example, the Netherlands currently charge €51 for permanent residency, and this charge will remain the same for obtaining a status under the Withdrawal Agreement.</p><p>Country-specific information, where available, is detailed in the ‘Living in Guides’ which you can find at:</p><p><a href="https://bit.ly/2PJAHjx" target="_blank">https://bit.ly/2PJAHjx</a></p><p>The Free Movement Directive sets out the registration requirements and the rules of charging for permanent residence that Member States must follow in their processes.</p><p>Under this Directive, a Member State can require a person living there for more than three months to register within a time frame, which should be no less than three months from the date of their arrival. The Directive also states that a citizen’s possession of such registration documents cannot be a precondition for exercising their Treaty rights. It provides that all documents, including registration certificates and permanent residence documents, shall be issued free of charge or for a charge that is no more than that which nationals of the Member State pay for a similar documents.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038975/answer",,,,,"207280","2019-01-16T16:24:15.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038975/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038975/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-01-10","Emigration: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what the financial costs are for a British citizen to acquire a permanent resident permit or the equivalent of such document in each European Union member state.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","207281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038976","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-01-18","<p>Rules surrounding the acquisition of citizenship in each European Union Member State, including cost, is a matter for that Member State’s authorities. Country-specific information on the cost of citizenship, where available, is given via the ‘Living in Guides’ which you can find at: <a href="https://bit.ly/2PJAHjx" target="_blank">https://bit.ly/2PJAHjx</a>. For instance, currently the cost of citizenship in Germany is €255 per person or, for children who are naturalised together with their parents, it is €51 per child.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038976/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-18T10:46:00.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038976/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038976/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-01-10","Emigration: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what are the financial costs for a British citizen to become a citizen of each European Union member state.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","207282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038977","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-17","<p>We will shortly consult on proposals for mandatory learning disability and autism training to ensure that staff working in health and social care understand the needs of people with learning disabilities and autism and have the skills to provide them with the most effective care and support. Officials have worked with people with lived experience of learning disabilities and autism to develop the consultation proposals.</p><p> </p><p>We want to hear a range of views, including those from people with a learning disability or autism and their families, and in line with Cabinet Office principles on consultation, we will tailor the consultation to meet the needs and preferences of different groups, including the provision of consultation documents in alternative formats.</p><p> </p><p>The consultation will consider the role of people with a learning disability or autism in the development and deployment of training as they can bring a unique and valuable perspective as users of health and care services.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038977/answer",,,,,"207284","2019-01-17T12:30:38.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038977/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038977/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-10","NHS: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to involve people with learning disabilities and autism in the development of mandatory training for NHS staff.","false","Biography information for Marsha De Cordova","Battersea","Marsha De Cordova","207283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038978","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-17","<p>We will shortly consult on proposals for mandatory learning disability and autism training to ensure that staff working in health and social care understand the needs of people with learning disabilities and autism and have the skills to provide them with the most effective care and support. Officials have worked with people with lived experience of learning disabilities and autism to develop the consultation proposals.</p><p> </p><p>We want to hear a range of views, including those from people with a learning disability or autism and their families, and in line with Cabinet Office principles on consultation, we will tailor the consultation to meet the needs and preferences of different groups, including the provision of consultation documents in alternative formats.</p><p> </p><p>The consultation will consider the role of people with a learning disability or autism in the development and deployment of training as they can bring a unique and valuable perspective as users of health and care services.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038978/answer",,,,,"207283","2019-01-17T12:30:38.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038978/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038978/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-10","NHS: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether mandatory training for NHS staff on learning disability and autism will involve people with learning disabilities and autism.","false","Biography information for Marsha De Cordova","Battersea","Marsha De Cordova","207284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038979","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-17","<p>The Long Term Plan, launched by the National Health Service on 7 January 2018, will transform patient care and make sure every penny of taxpayers’ money is spent wisely. This is supported by the Government’s investment of £20.5 billion a year in real terms by 2023/24. The additional funding will allow the NHS to get back on the path to delivering core performance standards. More than that, it will also drive the reforms that deliver a better and more sustainable NHS with improved care for patients.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, NHS England’s ‘Operational and Planning Guidance for 2019/20’ sets out deliverables against key performance areas and the Government has charged the NHS to deliver these actions set– in full – as key steps towards fully recovering performance against core access standards.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has also supported the NHS with an additional £1.6 billion for 2018/19 to improve emergency and elective performance. In addition, more than £420 million has been provided specifically for this winter.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038979/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-17T12:10:50.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038979/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038979/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-10","NHS: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to reduce waiting times for (a) NHS treatment in A&E, (b) routine operations, and (c) cancer care.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","207285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038980","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-17","<p>The NHS Long Term Plan outlines the expectation that all National Health Service funded care providers in England should have implemented the learning disability improvement standards by 2023/24.</p><p> </p><p>Inclusion of the improvement standards in the NHS Standard contract 2019/20, mandated by NHS England for use by commissioners of all healthcare services except primary care, means that all providers must have regard to the improvement standards and guidance.</p><p> </p><p>To monitor and ensure compliance with the standards, NHS Improvement has commissioned the NHS Benchmarking Network to facilitate national data collection across all NHS trusts, including NHS community trusts and NHS ambulance trusts.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038980/answer",,,,,"207287","2019-01-17T12:29:34.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038980/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038980/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-10","Health Services: Learning Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to ensure services funded by the NHS uphold national learning disability improvement standards; and whether he plans to bring forward measures to ensure compliance with those standards.","false","Biography information for Marsha De Cordova","Battersea","Marsha De Cordova","207286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038981","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-17","<p>The NHS Long Term Plan outlines the expectation that all National Health Service funded care providers in England should have implemented the learning disability improvement standards by 2023/24.</p><p> </p><p>Inclusion of the improvement standards in the NHS Standard contract 2019/20, mandated by NHS England for use by commissioners of all healthcare services except primary care, means that all providers must have regard to the improvement standards and guidance.</p><p> </p><p>To monitor and ensure compliance with the standards, NHS Improvement has commissioned the NHS Benchmarking Network to facilitate national data collection across all NHS trusts, including NHS community trusts and NHS ambulance trusts.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038981/answer",,,,,"207286","2019-01-17T12:29:34.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038981/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038981/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-10","Health Services: Learning Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what oversight his Department will give to services funded by the NHS in relation to the implementation of national learning disability improvement standards.","false","Biography information for Marsha De Cordova","Battersea","Marsha De Cordova","207287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038982","Treasury","false","2019-01-17","<p>Budget 2018 announced a two-year business rates discount of one third for small retailers. As set out in the published guidance, the government considers retail to mean properties being used as shops, cafes, restaurants, and drinking establishments. It will be for local authorities to implement the discount and decide whether properties are similar in nature to those listed as eligible in the guidance. Music venues will only be eligible where they are similar in nature to those properties listed as eligible.</p><p> </p><p>This discount is part of Our Plan for the High Street, a £1.5bn support package. All ratepayers are benefitting from recent wide-ranging reductions to business rates; in total, cuts announced since Budget 2016 are worth more than £13bn to businesses over the next five years.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038982/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-17T16:02:56.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038982/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038982/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-10","Licensed Premises: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has plans to assess the eligibility of music venues for discounted business rates.","true","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","207178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038983","Home Office","false","2019-01-17","<p>The Government has committed to putting into place the Windrush compensation scheme and is grateful to those who responded to the public consultation that closed on 16 November.</p><p>We are considering the outcome of the consultation exercise and will respond as soon as possible with further details, including who is eligible to apply for compensation and how they can access the scheme.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038983/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-17T16:38:01.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038983/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038983/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-01-10","Windrush Generation: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when he plans to publish details of the Windrush compensation scheme following the Government's consultation on that scheme.","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","207288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038984","Department for Transport","false","2019-01-15","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to the letter which my Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State wrote to him on 10 January.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038984/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-15T17:42:58.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038984/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038984/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-01-10","Portsmouth International Port: Road Traffic","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU without a deal on traffic levels around Portsmouth International Port.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","207289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038985","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-01-15","<p>As at 11 November 2019 there were 588 War Pension appeals in progress, of which 212 are waiting for a tribunal hearing date. Tribunal hearing dates are not set by the Ministry of Defence.</p><p>War Pensions Scheme statistics are published annually on the GOV.UK website at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/war-pension-recipients-index</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038985/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-15T15:36:34.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038985/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038985/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-01-10","War Pensions: Applications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many outstanding cases his Department is currently dealing with on disputes over applications for war pensions.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","207153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038986","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-01-15","<p>The current Estate Regeneration Fund is open to bids from local authorities that have partnered with a private organisation to deliver a regeneration project. The funding can be used for land clearance, demolition and rebuilding of homes. Low quality housing and high void rates can be prevalent in areas identified for regeneration and the funding that has been allocated will support places deliver better quality homes, improved public spaces and new housing where it is needed most.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038986/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-15T15:59:17.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038986/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038986/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-01-10","Housing: Regeneration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to he Answer of 9 January 2019 to Question 205256 on Housing: Regeneration, if he will create a fund for land clearance and the demolition of low quality, high void rate housing in circumstances whereby local authorities develop plans for housing regeneration.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","207223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038987","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-01-15","<p>We operate a zero earnings rule for Universal Credit in Support for Mortgage Interest (SMI). Receiving any earned income during the wait period or during receipt of SMI loan payments will mean that the claimant will not receive loan payments. The zero earnings rule requires claimants to satisfy a waiting period of nine consecutive Universal Credit assessment periods with no earned income before the claimants can receive loan payments.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to this we also work closely with UK Finance and Lenders to impress upon them importance of forbearance in the wait periods for SMI support.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038987/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-15T11:15:27.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038987/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038987/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-01-10","Universal Credit: Support for Mortgage Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the answer of 9 January 2019 to Question 205254 on Universal Credit: Support for Mortgage Interest, if she will ensure the rules in relation to support for mortgage interest loans mean that the 39 week waiting period is not reset when a claimant receives any income.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","207224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038988","Treasury","false","2019-01-17","<p>In 2017-18, Vehicle Excise Duty (VED) raised a total of around £6.2 billion in revenue.</p><p> </p><p>VED is collected nationwide and since it is tied to where individuals choose to register their vehicles, there is no official methodology to identify the VED collected in any particular region. As such, VED does not lend itself to devolution as vehicle registrations do not necessarily correlate with either emissions or vehicle use<em>.</em></p><p> </p><p>VED revenues will be hypothecated to the National Roads Fund (NRF) in England from 2020-21. The NRF will provide certainty for roads investment, including in London.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038988/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-17T14:06:02.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038988/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038988/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-10","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much money has been raised for the public purse from vehicle excise duties from the Greater London Authority area in each year for which information is available; and what assessment he has made of the potential merits of devolving the proceeds of vehicle excise duties raised in the Greater London Authority area to London local authorities.","false","Biography information for Julia Lopez","Hornchurch and Upminster","Julia Lopez","207290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038989","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-01-15","<p>The Government recognises the importance of providing clarity on the UK Shared Prosperity Fund and we intend to publish the public consultation shortly. Final decisions on the quantum and allocation of the Fund will be decided during the Spending Review this year.</p><p>In his Written Ministerial Statement of 24 July 2018 on Local Growth, HCWS927, the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government was clear the UK Shared Prosperity Fund will be a simplified, integrated fund that tackles inequalities between communities, by raising productivity. The Fund will be aligned to our modern Industrial Strategy.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038989/answer",,,,,"207292","2019-01-15T16:03:07.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038989/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038989/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-01-10","UK Shared Prosperity Fund: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether the funding allocated to Wales out of the UK Shared Prosperity fund will be as a result of a (a) pre-allocation or (b) competitive bidding process.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","207291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038990","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-01-15","<p>The Government recognises the importance of providing clarity on the UK Shared Prosperity Fund and we intend to publish the public consultation shortly. Final decisions on the quantum and allocation of the Fund will be decided during the Spending Review this year.</p><p>In his Written Ministerial Statement of 24 July 2018 on Local Growth, HCWS927, the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government was clear the UK Shared Prosperity Fund will be a simplified, integrated fund that tackles inequalities between communities, by raising productivity. The Fund will be aligned to our modern Industrial Strategy.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038990/answer",,,,,"207291","2019-01-15T16:03:07.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038990/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038990/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-01-10","UK Shared Prosperity Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether funding allocated from the UK Shared Prosperity Fund will be restricted to  specific funding streams and policy goals.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","207292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038991","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-17","<p>The National Health Service has been subject to its current public procurement rules since the EU Directive came into force in 2004. We will work with the NHS develop an approach to procurement that reflects the ambitions set out in the NHS Long Term Plan.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038991/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-17T12:07:24.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038991/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038991/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-10","NHS: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference paragraph 1 of page 114 of the NHS Long-Term Plan, when he plans to (a) revoke the National Health Service (Procurement, Patient Choice and Competition) (No 2) Regulations 2013 and (b) exclude the NHS from the Public Contract Regulations.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","207225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038992","Department for International Development","false","2019-01-15","<p>Supporting the 1.8 million people who are internally displaced by conflict in north east Nigeria is a priority for my department. The UK is the largest donor to the World Food Programme’s Emergency Operation in Nigeria, which provided food and cash assistance 1.3 million displaced people and host communities in need of life-saving humanitarian assistance in 2018. We have also helped over 80,000 very vulnerable people access appropriate assistance to protection services, including rape survivors, victims of trauma, and over 4,000 children who have been separated from their families. We are supporting over 100,000 children to access quality education in conflict affected areas, where over 1,000 schools have been destroyed.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038992/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-15T15:29:38.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038992/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038992/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-01-10","Nigeria: Internally Displaced People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to support internally displaced peoples in northern Nigeria.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","207154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038993","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-15","<p>The Department has received both letters regarding Dr Chris Day from the Rt. hon. Member for North Norfolk and the hon. Member for Ellesmore Port and Neston dated 26 July 2018 and 17 December 2018. Officials are carefully considering their contents and preparing responses and my Rt. Hon. Friend the Secretary of State will be responding to the hon. Members’ letters shortly.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038993/answer",,,,,"207179","2019-01-15T14:10:52.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038993/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038993/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-10","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, when he plans to respond to the letter from the right hon. Member for North Norfolk of 26 July 2018 in relation to Dr Chris Day.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","207165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038994","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-17","<p>We will shortly consult on proposals for mandatory learning disability and autism training to ensure that staff working in health and social care understand the needs of people with learning disabilities and autism and have the skills to provide them with the most effective care and support. Officials have worked with people with lived experience of learning disabilities and autism to develop the consultation proposals.</p><p> </p><p>We want to hear a range of views, including those from people with a learning disability or autism and their families, and in line with Cabinet Office principles on consultation, we will tailor the consultation to meet the needs and preferences of different groups, including the provision of consultation documents in alternative formats.</p><p> </p><p>The consultation will consider the role of people with a learning disability or autism in the development and deployment of training as they can bring a unique and valuable perspective as users of health and care services.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038994/answer",,,,,"207227","2019-01-17T12:31:47.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038994/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038994/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-10","NHS: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to include people with (a) learning disabilities and (b) autism in the development of mandatory training for NHS staff.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","207226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038995","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-17","<p>We will shortly consult on proposals for mandatory learning disability and autism training to ensure that staff working in health and social care understand the needs of people with learning disabilities and autism and have the skills to provide them with the most effective care and support. Officials have worked with people with lived experience of learning disabilities and autism to develop the consultation proposals.</p><p> </p><p>We want to hear a range of views, including those from people with a learning disability or autism and their families, and in line with Cabinet Office principles on consultation, we will tailor the consultation to meet the needs and preferences of different groups, including the provision of consultation documents in alternative formats.</p><p> </p><p>The consultation will consider the role of people with a learning disability or autism in the development and deployment of training as they can bring a unique and valuable perspective as users of health and care services.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038995/answer",,,,,"207226","2019-01-17T12:31:47.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038995/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1038995/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-10","NHS: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether mandatory training on learning disability and autism will include people with (a) learning disabilities and (b) autism.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","207227"
